\textbf{Planned Setup.}
The experimental tank will be a transparent rectangular container with adjustable filling ratios ($\phi = 0.4$--$0.7$), representing a 1:10 scaled ballast tank. A granular damper compartment will be mounted near the tank base and filled with spherical silica particles ($d_p = 2$\,mm). Oscillatory excitation will be imposed through horizontal sinusoidal motion with prescribed amplitude and frequency, corresponding to the dominant sloshing mode predicted by the SPH simulation.

\textbf{Measurement Plan.}
Free-surface elevations will be captured using high-speed imaging and tracked via particle image velocimetry (PIV). Wall impact pressures will be recorded using miniature piezoelectric sensors. The same quantities ($h(t)$, $p(t)$, $E_k(t)$, $\eta$) will be extracted from both experiments and simulations for direct quantitative comparison.

\textbf{Validation Metrics.}
Quantitative validation will be based on:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) between measured and simulated free-surface elevation;
  \item Relative deviation in peak wall pressure (target: <10\%);
  \item Comparison of total energy dissipation ratio $\eta$ between experimental and numerical results.
\end{itemize}

Although the experimental work is not yet completed, this framework provides a reproducible plan for validation once data become available. It ensures consistency between the numerical and physical models and allows the model’s predictive capability to be rigorously assessed.


\section{Simulation Setup}
This setup enables systematic testing of how granular damping influences sloshing-induced loads, thereby addressing the main research objective.
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{SPH--DEM Coupling:} The fluid is modeled using Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics (SPH), while the granular material is represented by the Discrete Element Method (DEM). 
    Bidirectional coupling accounts for drag, pressure, and buoyancy forces between fluid and particles.
    \item \textbf{Domain and Geometry:} A rectangular tank with adjustable fill level is used to represent a generic ballast tank. Granular dampers are modeled as enclosed particles of defined size and density.
    \item \textbf{Boundary Conditions:} Solid walls are treated as rigid, no-slip boundaries for the fluid, with collision handling for DEM particles.
    \item \textbf{Initial Conditions:} Fluid and particles are initially at rest. Perturbations are introduced via prescribed tank motion to initiate sloshing.
\end{itemize}

