\subsection{Energy Conservation Monitoring}

To assess numerical stability and distinguish physical dissipation from artificial
energy drift, the total mechanical energy of the system is tracked at each time step:
\[
E_{\text{total}}(t) = E_{\text{kinetic}} + E_{\text{potential}} + E_{\text{internal}},
\]
where $E_{\text{kinetic}}$ includes translational and rotational energy of both fluid
and particles, $E_{\text{potential}}$ accounts for gravitational potential, and
$E_{\text{internal}}$ represents elastic strain energy stored in DEM contacts.
The relative energy drift over a simulation of duration $T$ is:
\[
\Delta E_{\text{rel}} = \frac{|E_{\text{total}}(T) - E_{\text{total}}(0)|}
                              {E_{\text{total}}(0)}.
\]
For the explicit leapfrog integrator used here, $\Delta E_{\text{rel}}$ is expected
to remain below 1\% over typical simulation durations when the CFL condition is
satisfied~\parencite{monaghan2005}. Values exceeding 5\% indicate insufficient temporal
resolution or contact stiffness instability, prompting time-step refinement.

\subsection{Dimensionless Parameters}

Four key dimensionless numbers characterize the flow regimes and validate the
physical relevance of the simulations:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Reynolds number:} $\mathrm{Re} = \rho U L / \mu$, where $U$ is the
      characteristic velocity (e.g., peak sloshing velocity). Typical values in
      the small-scale validation are $\mathrm{Re} \approx 10^3$--$10^4$, indicating
      transitional or turbulent flow, though turbulence is not explicitly modeled.
\item \textbf{Froude number:} $\mathrm{Fr} = U / \sqrt{gL}$, measuring the ratio
      of inertial to gravitational forces. For sloshing, $\mathrm{Fr} \approx 0.1$--$0.3$
      confirms gravity-dominated dynamics.
\item \textbf{Stokes number:} $\mathrm{St} = \tau_p / \tau_f$, where
      $\tau_p = \rho_p d_p^2 / (18\mu)$ is the particle relaxation time and
      $\tau_f = L/U$ the flow time scale. Values near unity ($\mathrm{St} \approx 1$)
      indicate optimal particle--fluid coupling for energy dissipation.
\item \textbf{Weber number:} $\mathrm{We} = \rho U^2 L / \gamma$, quantifying
      surface-tension effects. With $\mathrm{We} \gg 1$ in the present setups,
      capillarity is negligible compared to inertia.
\end{itemize}
