\section{Parameter Selection and Sensitivity Analysis}
\label{sec:param_sensitivity}

This section details the selection of numerical and physical parameters used in the SPH--DEM simulations. Conducting a sensitivity analysis ensures that the observed damping performance is not an artifact of specific parameter choices but reflects the underlying physical behavior of the coupled liquid--particle system.

In the absence of industrial data, parameters were chosen based on literature values and physical reasoning. 
A systematic sensitivity study framework was established to examine the influence of each parameter on damping performance:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Particle size, shape, and number.
    \item Particle stiffness, restitution coefficient, and friction coefficient.
    \item Fluid density and viscosity.
    \item Tank fill level and damper placement.
\end{itemize}
For each simulation, energy dissipation, root-mean-square (RMS) amplitudes, and force fluctuations are computed to quantify damping effectiveness.

\subsection{Automated Sensitivity Analysis Pipeline}

To enable systematic parametric exploration, an automated analysis pipeline was developed using Python scripts available in the project repository (\texttt{Results/sensitivity\_analysis.py}). The workflow consists of:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Batch Simulation Execution:} The \texttt{batch\_parametric\_runs.py} script generates multiple simulation configurations with varied parameters and executes them via the headless runner.

\item \textbf{Metric Extraction:} Each simulation produces a time-series CSV log from which final-state performance metrics are extracted:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Final ship vertical position and maximum roll/pitch angles
    \item Surface height variation (standard deviation)
    \item Peak velocity and mean speed
    \item Final energy drift and drift range
    \item Mean kinetic energy
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{Correlation Analysis:} Spearman rank correlations ($\rho \in [-1,1]$) are computed between input parameters and output metrics. This nonparametric approach captures monotonic relationships without assuming linearity.

\item \textbf{Output Generation:} Results are exported as:
\begin{itemize}
    \item LaTeX table (\texttt{sensitivity\_table.tex}) for direct inclusion in thesis
    \item CSV correlation matrix for further analysis
    \item Heatmap visualization (\texttt{fig\_sensitivity.pdf})
\end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

Table~\ref{tab:sensitivity} presents the sensitivity analysis framework results. The infrastructure successfully executed multiple simulation runs and extracted performance metrics from each. As shown in Table~\ref{tab:baseline_run}, a representative 200-step simulation demonstrates the logging system capturing critical parameters including energy drift ($-1.8\%$), surface dynamics (mean height 2.20~m, variation 0.51~m), and velocity statistics (peak 2.3~m/s).

For meaningful correlation analysis, parametric variation is required across dimensions such as particle count, time-step size, viscosity, and damper mass ratio. The current batch execution framework (\texttt{batch\_parametric\_runs.py}) provides the foundation for systematic parameter sweeps. When extended with CLI arguments for physical parameters (currently only simulation duration varies), this pipeline will generate populated correlation matrices.

