\section{Uncertainty and Limitations}
This section discusses the main sources of uncertainty and methodological limitations associated with the SPH--DEM simulations. Recognizing these aspects is essential for assessing the robustness of the findings and for identifying directions where further refinement could enhance model accuracy.

Uncertainties arise primarily from numerical discretization, particle resolution, and the choice of material parameters. While the sensitivity analysis in Section~\ref{sec:sensitivity} helped constrain their influence, some degree of variability remains unavoidable in computational modeling.
All simulations are subject to uncertainties stemming from:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Choice of numerical parameters (particle resolution, time step, interaction models).
    \item Simplified geometry and boundary conditions relative to real ballast tanks.
    \item Assumptions in material properties and initial conditions.
\end{itemize}
Minor discrepancies between simulated and reference results can be attributed to simplified boundary conditions and scale differences between computational and experimental setups.

The computational cost restricted the simulation duration and the number of particles used, limiting the ability to explore very fine-scale interactions. Similarly, the SPH--DEM framework assumes spherical particles and neglects interstitial air effects, which may influence damping behavior in real systems. These limitations are acknowledged, and results are interpreted in a qualitative and parametric context rather than as absolute predictions.

Despite these limitations, the uncertainties are well characterized and do not compromise the overall validity of the observed damping trends. Acknowledging these constraints provides a transparent foundation for future studies seeking to extend the present model to larger scales or more complex physical conditions.

