\section{Kinetic Energy Measurement and Comparison}
\label{sec:kinetic-energy}

Kinetic energy is a key indicator of sloshing intensity and energy dissipation in ballast tank simulations. In this analysis, the time evolution of total kinetic energy is compared for three cases: no damper, medium damper, and heavy damper.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{No Damper:} The kinetic energy decays slowly, indicating minimal energy dissipation and persistent sloshing motion.
    \item \textbf{Medium Damper:} The kinetic energy decreases more rapidly, showing enhanced energy dissipation due to the granular damper.
    \item \textbf{Heavy Damper:} The fastest decay is observed, demonstrating the most effective damping and energy absorption.
\end{itemize}

The results confirm that granular dampers significantly increase energy dissipation in the system. The heavier the damper, the more pronounced the reduction in kinetic energy, leading to improved sloshing mitigation. This quantitative comparison supports the effectiveness of granular dampers in ballast tank applications.

