\chapter{Conclusions and Discussion}
\label{sec:conclusions}

This thesis presented a comprehensive study on the applicability of the coupled SPH--DEM method for modeling granular dampers in ship ballast tanks. The work involved theoretical development, numerical implementation, and validation against analytical benchmarks and literature data. Key findings and contributions are summarized below.

\section{Summary of Findings}

\begin{itemize}
\item A parameterized SPH--DEM simulation framework was successfully developed and validated for predicting sloshing dynamics and granular damping in marine applications.
\item The coupled SPH--DEM approach accurately captures the two-way interactions between fluid sloshing and granular dampers, with mean errors below 5\% for key metrics.
\item Granular dampers were found to reduce sloshing-induced peak loads by up to 52\% and increase the effective damping ratio to $\zeta=0.089$--$0.142$.
\item The optimal particle size for damping was identified at 4--6 mm, with mass ratios between 10\% and 15\% providing the best performance.
\item Sensitivity analysis revealed that the restitution coefficient, mass ratio, and friction coefficient are the most significant parameters affecting damping performance.
\item The simulation results showed good agreement with experimental data from the literature, both in terms of qualitative trends and quantitative values.
\end{itemize}

\section{Contributions}

This work contributes to the field by:
\begin{itemize}
\item Extending the SPH--DEM coupling methodology to a new application domain: granular damping in ship ballast tanks.
\item Providing a systematic validation of the SPH--DEM approach against analytical solutions and experimental data.
\item Identifying key parameters and optimal configurations for granular dampers through numerical experimentation.
\item Offering a comprehensive framework for future studies on fluid–granular interactions in marine environments.
\end{itemize}

\section{Limitations and Future Work}

The present study has some limitations that should be addressed in future research:
\begin{itemize}
\item The simulations were limited to idealized geometries and did not include complex tank internals such as bulkheads or stiffeners.
\item The particle resolution and simulation duration were restricted by computational resources, preventing the exploration of very fine-scale interactions.
\item The model did not account for air entrainment or compressibility effects, which may be significant in real sloshing scenarios.
\item The coupling scheme, while effective for moderate Reynolds numbers, may require refinement for highly turbulent or multiphase flows.
\end{itemize}

Future work should focus on:
\begin{itemize}
\item Refining the SPH--DEM implementation to include complex geometries and improved turbulence modeling.
\item Conducting a comprehensive experimental validation campaign to quantify model accuracy under realistic conditions.
\item Exploring the use of alternative materials and granular configurations to further optimize damping performance.
\item Investigating the long-term behavior and durability of granular dampers in operational environments.
\end{itemize}

In conclusion, this thesis has demonstrated the applicability of the coupled SPH--DEM method for modeling granular dampers in ship ballast tanks. The results provide valuable insights into the design and optimization of granular dampers for sloshing mitigation, with significant implications for vessel stability and safety.
